{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510067"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:23:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:23:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11488"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11488"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.01,0.34,0.19,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4119"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111349"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4119"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93479"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4639"},{"type":"tags","id":"4705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5084"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16159"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45016"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45318"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111349"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old Torres Strait Islander man presents to the General Practice clinic with a rash on his genitals for the past two weeks. He has a medical history of childhood asthma for which he uses inhaled salbutamol as required, stage 3 chronic kidney disease and acute interstitial nephritis following administration of a penicillin injection for tonsillitis 10 years ago. He does not take any regular medications. He is currently sexually active with casual male partners and does not use barrier protection. He denies any dysuria or dyspareunia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a painless, firm ulcer with indurated borders located on the mid-shaft of the penis. There are no other ulcers in the mouth, perianal or anal region. There is no evidence of purulent discharge from the urethra. There are multiple swollen, non-tender lymph nodes around the neck.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin","Oral prednisolone","Desensitisation therapy followed by intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin","Oral doxycycline","Oral valaciclovir"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a painless, firm ulcer with indurated borders on the penis, known as a chancre. This lesion is characteristic of primary syphilis, caused by the spirochete \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E and transmitted via sexual contact. The patient has several risk factors, including unprotected sexual activity and being a man who has sex with men (MSM). The presence of non-tender regional lymphadenopathy further supports the diagnosis of primary syphilis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBenzathine benzylpenicillin is used to treat tonsillitis in people at high-risk of rheumatic fever if compliance with a 10-day course of oral antibiotics is unlikely. This man provides a history of acute interstitial nephritis (AIN) - a delayed, T-cell mediated reaction to penicillin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eintramuscular benzathine penicillin G\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for primary syphilis, this patient\u0027s history of AIN means an alternative treatment option is required. \u003Cstrong\u003EDesensitisation therapy followed by intramuscular benzathine penicillin G\u003C/strong\u003E would only be appropriate for patients with a history of type I or IgE-mediated allergic response to penicillin. Delayed severe reactions include AIN, drug rash with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms, Stevens\u2013Johnson syndrome or toxic epidermal necrolysis, acute generalised exanthematous pustulosis and serum sickness. These are all contraindications to desensitisation therapy, as further life-threatening reactions can occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct choice in this scenario. It is an appropriate alternative treatment for primary syphilis in patients with contraindications to penicillin use where desensitisation is not appropriate. Specifically, it is an appropriate alternative for nonpregnant patients with primary syphilis who have a contraindication to penicillin, including those with severe delayed hypersensitivity reactios; this would be managed under expert guidance. Examples of severe delayed hypersensitivity reactions include drug rash with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms, Stevens\u2013Johnson syndrome/toxic epidermal necrolysis, severe blistering or desquamative rash, as well as reactions with major internal organ involvement (which includes acute interstitial nephritis, such as in this case). The typical regimen is doxycycline 100 mg orally twice daily for 14 days. Studies have shown that doxycycline has comparable efficacy to penicillin in treating early syphilis, with serological cure rates of approximately 95% at 6 months post-treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is a corticosteroid that is not indicated in the treatment of primary syphilis. It may be used in some cases of secondary syphilis to prevent the Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction, but will not treat the infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValaciclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral medication primarily used for herpes simplex virus infections. It is not effective against \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E and thus not indicated for syphilis treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while benzathine penicillin G remains the gold standard for syphilis treatment, the patient\u0027s history of a severe reaction to an antibiotic injection necessitates the use of an alternative antibiotic. Were the reaction to be allergic in nature, desensitisation could be considered. However, doxycycline is an effective and safe alternative in this situation. Follow-up serological testing is crucial to ensure treatment efficacy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first-line treatment for primary syphilis is intramuscular benzathine benzyl.","In patients with a history of severe delayed reactions to penicillin, desensitisation is contraindicated and alternative antibiotics should be used.","Doxycycline is an appropriate alternative treatment for primary syphilis in patients with penicillin allergy, with efficacy comparable to penicillin."],"references":["Li J, Zheng HY. Early syphilis: serological treatment response to doxycycline/tetracycline versus benzathine penicillin. J Infect Dev Ctries. 2014 Feb 13;8(2):228-32. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24518634/","Legendre DP, Muzny CA, Marshall GD, Swiatlo E. Antibiotic Hypersensitivity Reactions and Approaches to Desensitization. Clinical Infectious Diseases. 2013 Dec 23;58(8):1140\u20138. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/cid/article/58/8/1140/355853","Barreto EF, Rule AD. Management of Drug-Associated Acute Interstitial Nephritis. Kidney360. 2020 Jan 7;1(1):62-64. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8808494/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93479"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11488"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93479"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-13T08:39:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T08:40:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4119"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111349"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://